paragraphs.title: Importing required libraries
paragraphs.text:
%spark

// So we can access IRIS!
import com.intersystems.spark._
import com.intersystems.jdbc.IRISDriver

import spark.implicits._

import org.apache.spark.storage.StorageLevel
import org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrame

import org.apache.spark.sql.functions._
import org.apache.spark.ml.linalg._

// Transformers to prepare the features for training
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.VectorAssembler
import org.apache.spark.ml.feature.VectorIndexer

// Algorithms (Estimators) to train our models (Transformers)
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.RandomForestClassifier
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.DecisionTreeClassifier
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.GBTClassifier

// To Evaluate the model against the test data
import org.apache.spark.ml.evaluation.BinaryClassificationEvaluator

// Models
import org.apache.spark.ml.PipelineModel
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.RandomForestClassificationModel
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.DecisionTreeClassificationModel
import org.apache.spark.ml.classification.GBTClassificationModel

// Pipepeline to connect transformers and estimators 
import org.apache.spark.ml.Pipeline

// So we can export our final model to PMML
import com.intersystems.spark.ml._
import org.jpmml.sparkml._
import java.io.File

paragraphs.title: Reading the data from IRIS
paragraphs.text:
%spark

sqlContext.clearCache()
val df = spark.read.format("iris").option("query","PublishedABT.MLEncounterGetFeatures()").load()

df.cache()
df.count()

df.cache()

paragraphs.text:
%md

So, there are no rows with null cells.

Not too surprising, given that this is a synthetic data set, but it was the case with the real data, too; any null values were dealt with there in the cube creation. Let's take a look at the data.

paragraphs.title: Vector Assembler
paragraphs.text:
%md

We need to transform our features into vectors before giving them to the ML algorithms. For that, we use a class called VectorAssembler(). It will take an array of column names and build a single column in our dataframe that will include all the selected features.

msg.data: We need to transform our features into vectors before giving them to the ML algorithms. For that, we use a class called VectorAssembler(). It will take an array of column names and build a single column in our dataframe that will include all the selected features.

paragraphs.title: Vector Indexer
paragraphs.text:
%md

Spark needs to know if a feature is *categorical* or *numeric*. A categorical feature is something like Male/Female, Day of Week, etc. A numeric feature is (usually) a continuous value, though there are occasional cases where it makes sense to force an algorithm to look at something non-continuous as numeric.

We could define this by hand but, again, Spark can help us with that with a VectorIndexer. It will look each feature and figure out for us if it is a categorical feature or continuous feature. We must give it a hint, though. Parameter MaxCategories defines the maximum number of items a feature must have to be considered a category. There are thirty-one possible days of the month, and it makes more sense to treat them as categorical than continuous. We'll make sure MaxCategories is at least 32 (in case of a null, which would now be a 0). For the rest, we'll have to look.

Let's see how many distinct values we have in our columns:

paragraphs.title: On training the intial pipeline
paragraphs.text:
%md

Note that the pipeline before we get to the actual model is pre-trained on the entire data set. This is to ensure that all categories can be dealt with in the final vector assembler/indexer combination, even if the training/testing split eliminates a category from the training set and it isn't used in the actual model.

%spark

// Include as independent variables all non-discarded columns except Patient ID (which we will use to sample) and the dependent variable, whether the

for (c <- collist) println(c)

val vectorAssembler = new VectorAssembler() 
    .setInputCols(collist)
    .setOutputCol("rawFeatures")

val vectorIndexer = new VectorIndexer().setInputCol("rawFeatures").setOutputCol("features").setMaxCategories(35)

val pipeintro = new Pipeline().setStages(Array(vectorAssembler, vectorIndexer))
val pipeIntro = pipeintro.fit(df)

paragraphs.title: Decision Tree Results
paragraphs.text:
%md

This model's fit is barely acceptable, even only in the synthetic data. An AUC of 0.75 is wore than that found in the literature on real data with better methods. The difference between the training AUC and the test AUC means the model is significantly overfit (test AUC is lower than train AUC by more than a few percent), but if we change the parameters (other than minInstancesPerNode, which is there to safeguard against poor statistics in cases where there are very few examples of encounters with a particular combination of conditions, etc.

In the real data, the fit is very slightly worse, and in fact only slightly better than randomly guessing. Its AUC of roughly 0.51 is definitely worse than industry standard, though it's difficult to compare properly with the literature. It's also significantly  overfit, even for the best-behaving hyperparameters for this kind of model.

Next, we'll try a random forest model, which should reduce overfitting, likely increasing the test AUC.

paragraphs.title: Random Forest Results
paragraphs.text:
%md

A massive increase in performance is welcome. An AUC of almost 0.9 is, of course, highly unrealistic in health data, which does highlight the fact that this data is synthetc. (In real data, among other things, quality of care is always inherently prone to fluctuations, whether because of the experience levels of doctors and nursing staff, the workload of doctors and nursing staff, or possibly even the amount of coffee the doctors and nursing staff have recently had.) However, when applied to our real data, there was still a large improvement.

Specifically, with real data, we found an AUC of about 0.73, which says a random forest is probably a good model, though again it's difficult to compare properly with the literature; we had to compare with LACE to be sure. It's also much less overfit (test AUC is still lower than train AUC, but by a much smaller amount).

paragraphs.title: Boosted Tree Results
paragraphs.text:
%md

The boosted tree representation in this version of Spark ML doesn't work well with AUC, so the performance may be better than it looks. That said, we can't say for sure, and how it looks isn't much better in this case than the standard decision tree. Random forest is the best of the tree-based options.

select Prediction_Bucket, True_Readmission_Rate from PredictedVsActualProb

%md

Keep in mind here that the labels on the bottom are the bottom of the histogram bucket of predicted probability.

This is remarkably accurate until we get to around the 20-25% bucket, where it starts trending high (in the synthetic data; interestingly enough, this trend doesn't start in the real data until the next bucket, 25-30%); however, that's entirely reasonable, given how few samples there are at that point.
